===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|pece|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|pais||peace|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|pax|pāx|peace|lang=la}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|paḱ-|to fasten, stick, place|lang=en}}, related to Latin {{term|paciscor|pacīscor|agree, stipulate|lang=la}}, Latin {{term|pango|pangō|fasten, fix|lang=la}}; see [[pact]]. Displaced native [[Middle English]] {{term|frith|lang=enm}}, {{term|frede|lang=enm}} "peace" (from [[Old English]] ''[[friþ#Old English|friþ]]'', ''[[freod#Old English|frēod]]'' "peace"), Middle English ''[[sib#Middle English|sib, sibbe]]'' "peace" (from Old English ''[[sibb#Old English|sibb]]'' "peace, kinship"), Middle English ''[[grith#Middle English|grith]]'' "peace, security" (from [[Old English]] ''[[griþ#Old English|griþ]]'' and Old Norse ''[[grið#Old Norse|grið]]''), Middle English ''[[saught#Middle English|saht, saught]]'' "peace, reconciliation" (from Old English ''[[seht#Old English|seht]]'', ''[[sæht#Old English|sæht]]'' "peace, pact, agreement").

